I voted at @sjsu MLK Library today & it was easy! For Decline to State voters, if you don’t request a Democratic ballot by Tuesday, no worries, you can vote for President at a vote center. 22 in Santa Clara County opened today until Election Day, dozens more open next weekend!

And if you are a no party preference voter, as they check you in, they’ll ask if you’d like a Democratic ballot! (They don’t offer Republican ballot because Republican Party doesn’t allow it) I’m hoping people will try out a vote center before Election Day. It was great! @SCCgov

Then, stick the card in the machine and make your selections. After you are done, a paper ballot is printed out that you can double check is correct. You place that ballot in a receiving machine and you’re done. Easy! @SCCgov

I voted today at the new vote center at @sjsu MLK Library & it was a breeze! Someone checks you in & gives them your name and verify your DOB & address. You sign to verify it is actually you. Then you get a card to enter into a machine (you can choose just paper too).@sccvote

San José! If you want to check out a vote center, I’ll be voting today at the new vote center at MLK Library at @SJSU at 3 pm! Corner of San Fernando Street and 4th, 1st floor of the library. You can also ask for a Dem ballot there, register to vote & drop off completed ballots.

As a Bernie endorser, I agree he is our best bet to not just win and build a movement. But, the audacity of the billionaire class is exhausting.

I don’t care how many elected officials have jumped onto the Bloomberg train. The people know what he’s about & too many of our people that we all too often take for granted as Democrats will stay home if we force them to make this choice. Let’s fight for our party & our nation!

We need to bring in a coalition of voters who would otherwise stay at home. That’s what Obama did. We need young people, Latinos, African-Americans to feel like our party is fighting for them. Not simply that the current guy is bad.

Will money have us accept anyone who decides they want to lead our democracy, just because the current guy’s horrible? Don’t we have standards? Shouldn’t we fight for our democracy by engaging our citizenry & our grassroots, not whitewashing the troubling history of a billionaire

What happened to the morality of the Democratic Party all of a sudden? I thought we wanted money out of politics? I thought we agreed money is a troubling influence? Is this the new norm? Billionaires from here on out will literally buy the Presidency?

Yet, a billionaire with major issues who as Republican Mayor instituted and defended racist policies, has dozens of sexual harassment cases, a dramatically pro-charter school agenda & and an anti-worker agenda opposing minimum wage increases enters race vowing to spend billions.

We have 5 qualified, talented candidates atop the race for President that range from the center to the left of the Democratic Party. Bernie, Pete, Amy, Warren & Biden provide a great cross-section of candidates, all of whom would be monumentally better than our current President.

So, Democrats (rightfully so) are aghast at Trump’s misogyny, sexual harassment and abuse; and they raked Kamala Harris over the coals over her prosecutiorial record. Yet, there seems to be no hesitance to get behind stop-and-frisk & multiple sexual harassment cases Bloomberg?!

Ultimately, I believe, like healthcare, it is a public good that should be accessible without cost or as close as possible for everyone. The reality is the billionaires & millionaires raised taxes will cover much of the cost, so, it’s cool if their kids get a great, free degree.

The point is instead of criticizing the aspect of the college for all plan which is a tiny fraction of costs (billionaires & millionaires whose kids will got to public college) focus on how we make it free for the 98%. Capping at $100K won’t do that.

As in, I agree with the distraction of calling it a Republican talking point as it applies to free college. But, they would oppose anybofnthebllans with equal gusto. So, let’s push for college for all and make it a public good.

I agree with the Republican part. But, I do believe saying a college for all plan is a plan that helps the millionaires and billionaires (when their increased taxes is much of what will pay for the all part) is disingenuous and fear rather than fact based.

In the 1960s, the UC system had no tuition, only a $84 annual fee for one of the finest educations in the world. Many benefited from it & it helped make California a major economic force. That’s what a free public education does. It is an investment in our students & our economy.

Many countries offer free public college. And, argument can be used against many other public goods like K-12, social security, public safety. Means testing (& btw, an $100K cap leaves a wide delta between millionaires/billionaires & those who qualify) in will create fractures.

Don’t care about labels. Focusing on policy. It’s a poor argument as a Dem to attack College for All b/c of benefit to tiny fraction of very wealthy & use that fact to create fear amongst a larger base of voters. Let’s create a public good for all without apologies or exceptions.
